31
00:02:29,566 --> 00:02:32,361
<i>He was like that</i>
<i>ever since he lost Maki.</i>

32
00:02:35,322 --> 00:02:38,116
<i>-The number you're trying to reach--</i>
-What's he doing?!

33
00:02:41,995 --> 00:02:43,580
-Hello.
-Hold it.

34
00:02:43,914 --> 00:02:45,374
I don't think you work here.

35
00:02:46,333 --> 00:02:48,919
Showing me the inside of your coat
won't help.

36
00:02:49,920 --> 00:02:52,089
-Who are you?
-I'm Yamashita.

37
00:02:52,255 --> 00:02:54,883
That's not much help.
Which "Yamashita" are you?

38
00:02:54,966 --> 00:02:56,051
The straight man.

39
00:02:56,259 --> 00:02:58,011
-Once more.
-Here I go.

40
00:03:01,473 --> 00:03:03,809
-You're worse than I thought.
-Ready?

41
00:03:06,103 --> 00:03:08,271
-Come on.
-You're throwing the ball.

42
00:03:08,480 --> 00:03:09,856
-That's not a serve.
-Hit it back.

43
00:03:09,940 --> 00:03:11,858
I can't tell when it'll come.

44
00:03:11,983 --> 00:03:13,527
Once more.

45
00:03:14,945 --> 00:03:16,905
-Hit it back properly.
-Let me serve.

46
00:03:16,988 --> 00:03:18,198
Here I go.

47
00:03:19,574 --> 00:03:20,826
Come on!

48
00:03:26,039 --> 00:03:27,916
You hit the ceiling!

49
00:03:29,918 --> 00:03:31,545
<i>The wounds were deep.</i>

50
00:03:32,295 --> 00:03:34,339
<i>They took a long time to heal.</i>

51
00:04:19,676 --> 00:04:23,847
HIBANA
- Spark -

52
00:04:29,102 --> 00:04:30,896
-Hello.
-Hello.

53
00:04:31,897 --> 00:04:34,441
BABY HOSHIKAWA'S "TALK-IINO"
MON 24:00 - 27:00

54
00:04:35,901 --> 00:04:36,902
Hello!

55
00:04:37,152 --> 00:04:38,320
-Hello.
-Hi!

56
00:04:38,445 --> 00:04:39,654
Hello.

57
00:04:39,821 --> 00:04:40,781
Hello.

58
00:04:40,906 --> 00:04:41,907
Hello.

59
00:04:42,240 --> 00:04:43,158
Hello.

60
00:04:44,201 --> 00:04:46,828
Mr. Hoshikawa, thanks for
having us on <i>Talk-iino.</i>

61
00:04:46,912 --> 00:04:48,872
-Don't let me down.
-Thank you!

62
00:04:48,955 --> 00:04:50,165
Introduce yourself.

63
00:04:50,332 --> 00:04:52,918
-I'm Yamashita from Sparks.
-I'm Sakamoto.

64
00:04:53,752 --> 00:04:55,670
This guy's a real pro.

65
00:04:56,254 --> 00:04:57,881
-He's the guru?
-He is.

66
00:04:57,964 --> 00:05:00,634
-Wow.
-This is your big chance.

67
00:05:00,759 --> 00:05:02,010
It's our big chance?

68
00:05:02,928 --> 00:05:04,930
Where's your partner? Tokunaga.

69
00:05:06,056 --> 00:05:07,349
He's, um...

70
00:05:07,516 --> 00:05:10,894
The nerves have got to his stomach.
He's stuck on the toilet.

71
00:05:12,896 --> 00:05:14,898
Don't you get sick of shadow boxing?

72
00:05:18,944 --> 00:05:20,529
I'll be right back.

73
00:05:21,029 --> 00:05:22,489
Mr. Kamiya...

74
00:05:22,572 --> 00:05:24,199
INSTANT LOANS

75
00:05:24,366 --> 00:05:26,785
How about calling it a night?

76
00:05:26,993 --> 00:05:28,787
You have plans?

77
00:05:28,912 --> 00:05:30,330
Sorry.

78
00:05:35,335 --> 00:05:36,503
You're right.

79
00:05:37,128 --> 00:05:38,672
Let's call it a night.

80
00:05:41,258 --> 00:05:43,927
-Just one more drink?
-It's okay.

81
00:05:47,931 --> 00:05:49,182
Ready...

82
00:05:54,479 --> 00:05:56,064
Ready!

83
00:05:58,567 --> 00:05:59,901
See ya!

84
00:06:07,909 --> 00:06:09,286
Speak up!

85
00:06:09,411 --> 00:06:10,579
Yessir! Sorry!

86
00:06:10,745 --> 00:06:13,081
We'll be on soon!
Could you please standby?

87
00:06:13,206 --> 00:06:14,624
Okay.

88
00:06:24,968 --> 00:06:29,180
"There's a guy at school
who always plays weird tricks on me.

89
00:06:29,347 --> 00:06:32,976
How can I stop it without offending him?
In need of some advice."

90
00:06:33,059 --> 00:06:36,438
So, they're in a bit of trouble.
I guess in situations like these...

91
00:06:37,022 --> 00:06:39,065
Excuse me.
You'll be on soon.

92
00:06:40,066 --> 00:06:42,360
You'll be on soon. It's time to standby!

93
00:06:42,485 --> 00:06:43,987
Sure thing. Thanks.

94
00:06:44,195 --> 00:06:47,240
-Where is your partner?
-My partner... Hm?

95
00:06:48,283 --> 00:06:50,201
It's still warm. He should be close by.

96
00:06:50,952 --> 00:06:52,454
NIPPON BROADCASTING RADIO

97
00:07:12,098 --> 00:07:14,142
-Hey! You're late!
-Sorry.

98
00:07:14,309 --> 00:07:16,436
-You're late!
-I'm hot.

99
00:07:16,978 --> 00:07:18,521
I haven't run for ages.

100
00:07:18,688 --> 00:07:21,232
Who cares?
Hurry up and get changed.

101
00:07:22,859 --> 00:07:24,235
What's with that?

102
00:07:25,987 --> 00:07:28,156
Don't strip it off.
There's a lady behind you.

103
00:07:28,281 --> 00:07:30,909
-I got you one, too.
-I'm not wearing it.

104
00:07:30,992 --> 00:07:33,370
Why put on a silly costume
for a radio show?

105
00:07:34,579 --> 00:07:37,540
You really do have one for me?
I'm not wearing it!

106
00:07:37,666 --> 00:07:38,959
Where were you?

107
00:07:39,751 --> 00:07:41,294
I was thinking of a new punchline.

108
00:07:41,419 --> 00:07:43,964
-But let's keep the original.
-What?

109
00:07:44,089 --> 00:07:45,590
I nearly had a heart attack--

110
00:07:48,635 --> 00:07:50,053
Blow for me.

111
00:07:50,887 --> 00:07:51,972
Blow!

112
00:07:52,097 --> 00:07:53,348
That's inhaling!

113
00:07:53,515 --> 00:07:54,975
You stink of alcohol!

114
00:07:55,141 --> 00:07:57,602
Were you with Mr. Kamiya again?

115
00:07:57,894 --> 00:07:59,270
-I'm sober now.
-You're drunk?

116
00:07:59,437 --> 00:08:00,730
-I sweated it out.
-You're--

117
00:08:00,897 --> 00:08:01,940
Boys.

118
00:08:02,524 --> 00:08:03,984
-Hello.
-Hello.

119
00:08:04,442 --> 00:08:06,987
Can you shorten your two-minute act
to 30 seconds?

120
00:08:07,278 --> 00:08:09,364
-Thirty seconds?
-We're running over time.

121
00:08:09,489 --> 00:08:10,865
-Two minutes...
-Sorry.

122
00:08:10,949 --> 00:08:13,034
-You're telling us now?
-I'm counting on you!

123
00:08:13,243 --> 00:08:16,079
...today's guest were Sparks!

124
00:08:16,162 --> 00:08:18,957
-Thanks, guys.
-Thank you.

125
00:08:21,376 --> 00:08:22,335
Thanks, guys.

126
00:08:22,502 --> 00:08:23,920
-Thank you.
-Thank you.

127
00:08:24,713 --> 00:08:25,797
Thank you.

128
00:08:30,343 --> 00:08:31,970
-Excuse us.
-Thank you!

129
00:08:34,389 --> 00:08:35,515
Thanks, guys.

130
00:08:35,890 --> 00:08:36,933
Thank you.

131
00:08:37,017 --> 00:08:39,894
If the feedback is good,
we'll see you again soon.

132
00:08:40,228 --> 00:08:41,813
-Thank you.
-Thank you.

133
00:09:03,585 --> 00:09:05,628
Thank you, Speaks!

134
00:09:22,520 --> 00:09:25,857
SPEAKS, SPHYNX, SPIELBERG, SUPERMANS...

135
00:09:39,913 --> 00:09:41,915
HYUGA AGENCY

136
00:09:54,010 --> 00:09:55,762
-Good morning.
-Good morning, sir!

137
00:09:56,846 --> 00:09:57,931
You got me.

138
00:09:59,766 --> 00:10:01,142
Is that an impersonation?

139
00:10:02,227 --> 00:10:03,186
The Tokuma Pose!

140
00:10:03,812 --> 00:10:04,729
That's cool.

141
00:10:04,813 --> 00:10:06,940
Where should it go, Ms. Erika?

142
00:10:07,065 --> 00:10:09,567
-Hm... A little higher.
-Higher?

143
00:10:09,734 --> 00:10:11,111
-That's too high.
-Sorry.

144
00:10:11,236 --> 00:10:13,113
BUU FUBUUBU
ON AIR TUESDAYS

145
00:10:13,238 --> 00:10:15,573
If you put that there,

146
00:10:15,740 --> 00:10:18,076
Mr. Tokuma won't stand out.

147
00:10:18,159 --> 00:10:20,620
But, boss, it won't fit.
You can't hang it sideways.

148
00:10:21,121 --> 00:10:23,331
How about...? Oh, that won't work either.

149
00:10:23,498 --> 00:10:25,375
-There's no point.
-You're right.

150
00:10:26,334 --> 00:10:28,461
-You're here?
-Good morning.

151
00:10:30,088 --> 00:10:31,381
Mr. Ogata...

152
00:10:31,881 --> 00:10:34,008
Let me apologize about the radio show.

153
00:10:34,134 --> 00:10:37,011
But we had to cut it to 30 seconds,
just before the show.

154
00:10:37,137 --> 00:10:38,888
We'd practiced a two-minute routine.

155
00:10:38,972 --> 00:10:41,933
-They told us at the last moment.
-It was a bit unfair.

156
00:10:42,016 --> 00:10:43,977
What are you babbling about?

157
00:10:45,270 --> 00:10:47,147
You got a gig.

158
00:10:48,273 --> 00:10:49,899
The <i>New Comedy Star Battle</i>.

159
00:10:52,652 --> 00:10:53,903
Give me one.

160
00:10:53,987 --> 00:10:55,613
-For real?
-For real?!

161
00:10:57,115 --> 00:10:59,284
-The <i>New Comedy Star Battle</i>!
-I know.

162
00:10:59,409 --> 00:11:00,618
Is this real?

163
00:11:00,785 --> 00:11:02,871
Everyone in the industry comes.

164
00:11:02,954 --> 00:11:05,874
For better or worse, they'll remember you.

165
00:11:05,957 --> 00:11:07,167
They will...

166
00:11:07,333 --> 00:11:10,920
Buu Fubuubu were in this contest
last year, right?

167
00:11:11,254 --> 00:11:14,173
The moment they won,
they got three weekly shows.

168
00:11:14,507 --> 00:11:15,925
Three weekly shows?

169
00:11:16,259 --> 00:11:17,552
This is insane.

170
00:11:17,635 --> 00:11:19,554
That's <i>if</i> we win.

171
00:11:19,929 --> 00:11:22,891
If you do well,
the <i>New Star Battle </i>is a big chance.

172
00:11:23,057 --> 00:11:25,059
But if you mess up,
the damage is big, too.

173
00:11:25,643 --> 00:11:26,561
Damage?

174
00:11:26,895 --> 00:11:28,771
According to Buu Fubuubu,

175
00:11:28,897 --> 00:11:31,232
it's all about
how much the audience laugh.

176
00:11:33,526 --> 00:11:35,570
It's not like your previous gigs.

177
00:11:35,737 --> 00:11:37,030
Keep the masses in mind.

178
00:11:37,113 --> 00:11:39,115
Why not make your routine simpler?

179
00:11:42,911 --> 00:11:46,164
"It's important that you realize
what people want from you.

180
00:11:46,331 --> 00:11:49,876
Not only when you have sex,
but in every situation."

181
00:11:50,668 --> 00:11:52,962
Wisdom from the god of porn, Taka Kato.

182
00:11:53,588 --> 00:11:54,422
Bye.

183
00:11:54,923 --> 00:11:55,924
Okay!

184
00:11:59,928 --> 00:12:04,098
You got in thanks to the recommendation
from the writer, Isshin Takada.

185
00:12:05,308 --> 00:12:07,894
Do it like you always do.

186
00:12:08,895 --> 00:12:09,812
See?

187
00:12:09,896 --> 00:12:11,481
GO WITH THE FLOW

188
00:12:11,648 --> 00:12:12,815
Go for it.

189
00:12:18,696 --> 00:12:20,949
It's the <i>New Star Battle.</i>
What'll we do?

190
00:12:21,115 --> 00:12:22,951
I'm thinking.
Don't rush me.

191
00:12:23,326 --> 00:12:24,869
You heard Mr. Ogata.

192
00:12:24,953 --> 00:12:26,746
"Keep the masses in mind."

193
00:12:26,829 --> 00:12:28,915
It's all about how much
the audience laugh.

194
00:12:29,749 --> 00:12:31,459
Remember what Mr. Takada wrote?

195
00:12:31,918 --> 00:12:35,171
"Sparks is unique."
That's what he liked.

196
00:12:39,008 --> 00:12:40,760
But he's a pro.

197
00:12:40,927 --> 00:12:42,887
We want everyone to laugh.

198
00:12:43,221 --> 00:12:45,890
We want to be popular with the masses.

199
00:12:46,307 --> 00:12:47,642
You write it.

200
00:12:47,809 --> 00:12:49,394
That won't work.

201
00:12:49,894 --> 00:12:53,481
My role is to keep the same perspective
as the audience.

202
00:12:57,443 --> 00:12:58,861
Have you read the comments online?

203
00:12:58,945 --> 00:13:02,323
"The funny man from Sparks is gloomy."
"He's unrelatable."

204
00:13:04,742 --> 00:13:05,910
I know.

205
00:13:17,922 --> 00:13:19,590
The <i>New Star Battle</i>...

206
00:13:19,674 --> 00:13:20,883
We won it.

207
00:13:20,967 --> 00:13:23,553
What's with all the confidence?

208
00:13:27,265 --> 00:13:28,891
-Tokunaga.
-What?

209
00:13:29,684 --> 00:13:30,893
The <i>New Star Battle</i>...

210
00:13:31,019 --> 00:13:32,061
We won it.

211
00:13:32,603 --> 00:13:33,688
Thanks, everyone.

212
00:13:33,855 --> 00:13:34,897
-It's great.
-I know.

213
00:13:35,023 --> 00:13:36,441
I think it'll work.

214
00:13:36,941 --> 00:13:38,443
Let's run it through.

215
00:13:39,110 --> 00:13:41,237
-Hello, we're Sparks.
-Please enjoy the show.

216
00:13:41,487 --> 00:13:43,948
-Dial it again.
-Bip, bop, bap. Prrr...

217
00:13:44,115 --> 00:13:47,910
The number you're trying to reach
belongs to artificial intelligence.

218
00:13:47,994 --> 00:13:49,412
It has formed its own identity.

219
00:13:49,495 --> 00:13:52,290
It is busy planning
the extinction of the human race.

220
00:13:52,373 --> 00:13:54,876
-Sorry, but we cannot connect you.
-Stop it!

221
00:13:54,959 --> 00:13:56,669
That's way too scary!

222
00:13:58,504 --> 00:14:01,466
I don't know, but maybe you could...

223
00:14:01,674 --> 00:14:04,761
Don't you have a joke
that younger audiences will like?

224
00:14:05,720 --> 00:14:07,722
A joke that's more pop.

225
00:14:07,889 --> 00:14:10,308
-We don't need to be pop.
-Do you have one?

226
00:14:15,354 --> 00:14:17,899
How about this?
-Bip, bop, bop. Prrr...

227
00:14:17,982 --> 00:14:20,193
-Call telephone. No reception--
-Hey. Hey!

228
00:14:20,360 --> 00:14:22,320
Come on. Do it properly.

229
00:14:22,904 --> 00:14:23,946
Bip, bop, bap. Prrr...

230
00:14:24,113 --> 00:14:26,949
Call telephone.
No reception. Or switch off!

231
00:14:27,200 --> 00:14:28,534
Fuck!

232
00:14:28,910 --> 00:14:30,620
Hey, come on.

233
00:14:31,287 --> 00:14:33,623
-Too much?
-What's with all the energy?

234
00:14:33,706 --> 00:14:36,125
But that's probably better. Any others?

235
00:14:37,877 --> 00:14:39,712
Jokes like that. Energetic ones.

236
00:14:39,796 --> 00:14:40,963
How about this?

237
00:14:41,672 --> 00:14:44,884
-Hello, young friends--
-You can be more pumped up.

238
00:14:45,426 --> 00:14:46,302
Hello, young friends!

239
00:14:46,469 --> 00:14:49,430
I'm in the fairy forest,
singing with my bird friends!

240
00:14:49,597 --> 00:14:53,017
Hop on a Pegasus,
and join us across the rainbow bridge!

241
00:14:53,184 --> 00:14:54,685
That's good.

242
00:14:54,894 --> 00:14:56,813
It's easy to understand. It's good.

243
00:14:56,896 --> 00:14:59,148
-Let's do that.
-I don't really like it.

244
00:14:59,607 --> 00:15:00,900
But let's try it.

245
00:15:01,526 --> 00:15:02,902
Bip, bop, bap. Prrr...

246
00:15:03,027 --> 00:15:03,903
Hello, young friends!

247
00:15:03,986 --> 00:15:07,115
I'm in the fairy forest,
singing with my bird friends!

248
00:15:07,240 --> 00:15:09,409
Hop on a Pegasus, and join us--

249
00:15:09,575 --> 00:15:13,371
-Aren't we sucking up too much?
-This is perfect for the <i>New Star Battle</i>.

250
00:15:13,579 --> 00:15:16,082
It's so cheesy. Do we need it?

251
00:15:16,207 --> 00:15:17,708
If we want to make a living.

252
00:15:24,757 --> 00:15:26,926
Bip, bop, bap, bop...

253
00:15:29,053 --> 00:15:31,180
Something just drove by. What was it?

254
00:15:31,389 --> 00:15:32,890
"Bip, bop, bap, bop."

255
00:15:34,767 --> 00:15:36,060
I wonder...

256
00:15:36,227 --> 00:15:38,396
Was it a police car? An ambulance?

257
00:15:39,397 --> 00:15:42,233
What made that sound?
"Bip, bop, bap, bop."

258
00:15:45,945 --> 00:15:48,865
What drove by? "Bip, bop, bap, bop."

259
00:15:49,532 --> 00:15:53,286
Ah, I know. It was a "bippobapo-bus."

260
00:15:55,746 --> 00:15:57,415
Hello. Sorry for the wait.

261
00:15:59,459 --> 00:16:01,961
-Where shall we go?
-Wherever we can drink.

262
00:16:02,128 --> 00:16:03,921
We've got sushi...

263
00:16:04,922 --> 00:16:06,132
Soba noodles...

264
00:16:06,466 --> 00:16:07,842
Mr. Kamiya.

265
00:16:07,925 --> 00:16:11,429
Why don't we buy something here
and drink in a park somewhere?

266
00:16:12,805 --> 00:16:14,307
This will do?

267
00:16:14,474 --> 00:16:17,768
I really like these little delicatessens.

268
00:16:18,686 --> 00:16:20,146
You like it trashy.

269
00:16:20,897 --> 00:16:22,899
You win. I'll keep you company.

270
00:16:23,774 --> 00:16:24,901
Welcome.

271
00:16:25,568 --> 00:16:26,777
What would you like?

272
00:16:26,861 --> 00:16:29,947
The most expensive is shrimp tempura.
Ten of them?

273
00:16:31,324 --> 00:16:32,909
That much shrimp?

274
00:16:32,992 --> 00:16:34,702
What do you want?

275
00:16:42,710 --> 00:16:43,920
Tokunaga.

276
00:16:59,894 --> 00:17:01,896
Wanna walk to Nikotama?

277
00:17:05,024 --> 00:17:06,567
Mr. Kamiya...

278
00:17:06,984 --> 00:17:09,654
I don't want my bag to
stink of fried chicken.

279
00:17:09,820 --> 00:17:11,614
Can we eat this first?

280
00:17:12,156 --> 00:17:15,701
Nothing whets your appetite more than
the aroma of fried chicken.

281
00:17:15,826 --> 00:17:18,329
If you think it smells bad
when it comes from your bag,

282
00:17:18,496 --> 00:17:20,957
your mind's just playing tricks on you.

283
00:17:21,707 --> 00:17:22,792
It's cool.

284
00:17:22,917 --> 00:17:24,252
Shit's cool!

285
00:17:28,381 --> 00:17:31,759
<i>There were so many things</i>
<i>I wanted to ask Mr. Kamiya.</i>

286
00:17:32,760 --> 00:17:34,387
You should walk more.

287
00:17:34,512 --> 00:17:39,684
<i>Apparently I'm convinced he knows</i>
<i>the answer to everything.</i>

288
00:17:39,767 --> 00:17:41,769
When you walk around, you realize things.

289
00:17:43,896 --> 00:17:47,650
There are so many funny things
just waiting for you to notice them.

290
00:17:47,858 --> 00:17:49,902
Take care, old lady.

291
00:18:02,707 --> 00:18:04,917
-Something happened.
-I wonder what.

292
00:18:05,918 --> 00:18:07,211
It looks okay.

293
00:18:25,896 --> 00:18:29,900
Mr. Kamiya, don't you ever worry
about other people's opinions?

294
00:18:30,359 --> 00:18:31,902
Where's this coming from?

295
00:18:33,195 --> 00:18:36,907
Well, it pisses me off
when people talk bad about me.

296
00:18:37,241 --> 00:18:38,826
But I don't really care.

297
00:18:39,118 --> 00:18:41,495
Even if they badmouth you
on the Internet?

298
00:18:43,789 --> 00:18:48,794
On the Internet, so many people talk
about others like they were trash.

299
00:18:49,295 --> 00:18:51,922
When that hate gets aimed your way,
it hurts.

300
00:18:52,298 --> 00:18:54,133
I'd rather be punched.

301
00:18:54,675 --> 00:18:57,178
It even drives some people to suicide.

302
00:18:58,012 --> 00:18:59,889
I think it's insane.

303
00:19:02,725 --> 00:19:03,934
But...

304
00:19:05,144 --> 00:19:06,979
think about the hater.

305
00:19:07,772 --> 00:19:11,942
If hating is the only thing they can do
to make it through the night alive,

306
00:19:12,109 --> 00:19:13,903
I think it's okay.

307
00:19:15,905 --> 00:19:19,909
I hope they write the most painful thing
about me they can think of.

308
00:19:25,289 --> 00:19:28,250
But I can't ignore them.

309
00:19:30,294 --> 00:19:33,714
If you worry about what people think,
you'll wear yourself out.

310
00:19:33,923 --> 00:19:38,219
In the end, will their words
have any effect on what you create?

311
00:19:39,637 --> 00:19:41,597
It'll make no difference.

312
00:19:44,016 --> 00:19:46,018
We're not that smart.

313
00:19:46,769 --> 00:19:48,562
We do what we want.

314
00:19:49,188 --> 00:19:51,607
If it's funny, we'll make a living.

315
00:19:51,899 --> 00:19:53,859
If it's not, we'll get weeded out.

316
00:19:53,943 --> 00:19:55,403
That's all.

317
00:20:01,826 --> 00:20:04,120
<i>We weren't making a living.</i>

318
00:20:05,955 --> 00:20:08,124
<i>Were we not funny?</i>

319
00:20:18,801 --> 00:20:21,262
Kudos to the food of the masses.

320
00:20:21,721 --> 00:20:23,889
It tastes great even when it's cold.

321
00:20:24,223 --> 00:20:27,017
How rude of you
to complain about its smell.

322
00:20:51,542 --> 00:20:52,877
Damn.

323
00:20:53,919 --> 00:20:55,171
That stinks!

324
00:21:11,896 --> 00:21:12,730
Tokunaga.

325
00:21:13,689 --> 00:21:14,857
Come on in.

326
00:21:17,902 --> 00:21:19,028
-Hi.
-Hello.

327
00:21:19,195 --> 00:21:21,906
-Sorry for making you wait.
-Sorry for calling you in.

328
00:21:22,198 --> 00:21:24,116
-Was it hard to find?
-A little.

329
00:21:24,241 --> 00:21:25,367
Wow.

330
00:21:25,951 --> 00:21:27,161
-Cool?
-Yes.

331
00:21:27,328 --> 00:21:29,705
<i>There was an unwritten rule</i>
<i>for young comedians:</i>

332
00:21:29,830 --> 00:21:33,876
<i>Don't mix with the juniors</i>
<i>that your partner is close with.</i>

333
00:21:33,959 --> 00:21:35,961
-Beer, please.
-Beer?

334
00:21:36,128 --> 00:21:38,339
-I'll have an Oolong & Shochu.
-Coming up.

335
00:21:41,884 --> 00:21:44,887
-You're doing well lately.
-Not at all.

336
00:21:45,221 --> 00:21:47,264
We're still as poor as ever.

337
00:22:02,905 --> 00:22:04,240
Have you heard?

338
00:22:06,909 --> 00:22:08,202
About Kamiya.

339
00:22:09,912 --> 00:22:14,291
He's in so much debt,
he's nearly beyond help.

340
00:22:16,961 --> 00:22:19,296
You know. When he's with you,

341
00:22:19,964 --> 00:22:21,882
he tries to act too big.

342
00:22:24,009 --> 00:22:27,179
I know that's part of
what makes him funny, but...

343
00:22:28,764 --> 00:22:31,475
unless something changes,
we won't be able to do <i>manzai</i> anymore.

344
00:22:32,977 --> 00:22:34,186
I'm sorry.

345
00:22:35,145 --> 00:22:37,773
He always pays for me.

346
00:22:38,065 --> 00:22:40,192
-From now on, I'll try to--
-No.

347
00:22:40,359 --> 00:22:43,362
That's not what I mean.
You should stay close with him.

348
00:22:44,613 --> 00:22:45,906
Stay close.

349
00:22:50,911 --> 00:22:52,955
Are you in the next
<i>New Comedy Star Battle</i>?

350
00:22:53,122 --> 00:22:54,623
Yes.

351
00:22:54,790 --> 00:22:55,916
We're in it, too.

352
00:22:56,083 --> 00:22:57,876
Ahondara will be, too?

353
00:22:57,960 --> 00:22:59,169
You didn't know?

354
00:22:59,920 --> 00:23:01,130
Kamiya didn't tell you?

355
00:23:02,506 --> 00:23:04,008
-He did.
-He did?

356
00:23:04,883 --> 00:23:08,178
But he hasn't decided
which act we should do.

357
00:23:10,889 --> 00:23:13,017
The <i>New Star Battle</i>...

358
00:23:13,559 --> 00:23:16,353
You know how duos break up
if they don't do well?

359
00:23:17,229 --> 00:23:20,316
It might be our very last chance.

360
00:23:24,111 --> 00:23:25,654
What do you mean?

361
00:23:25,904 --> 00:23:27,364
Don't get me wrong.

362
00:23:27,615 --> 00:23:28,949
We're not gonna quit.

363
00:23:29,700 --> 00:23:31,201
Don't write us off.

364
00:23:34,997 --> 00:23:36,206
Sorry.

365
00:23:37,374 --> 00:23:38,917
But Kamiya...

366
00:23:39,918 --> 00:23:42,671
When he talks about you,
he always looks so happy.

367
00:23:43,881 --> 00:23:45,633
He really must like you.

368
00:23:46,425 --> 00:23:47,635
Kamiya...

369
00:23:48,927 --> 00:23:49,928
He likes you.

370
00:23:55,142 --> 00:23:57,645
The big time... Wouldn't that be nice?

371
00:24:06,737 --> 00:24:08,113
Bip, bop, bap. Prrr...

372
00:24:09,281 --> 00:24:13,118
It is with profound regret that I inform
you this number is currently unavailable.

373
00:24:13,285 --> 00:24:16,789
-Please forgive me. Please, pretty please!
-That message is too polite!

374
00:24:16,872 --> 00:24:18,749
"Please, pretty please!"?

375
00:24:18,874 --> 00:24:21,043
And there's no need to bow.
Nobody can see you.

376
00:24:21,210 --> 00:24:23,545
And stop doing that giggle at the end.

377
00:24:23,712 --> 00:24:26,590
I didn't like it the first time.
No more giggling.

378
00:24:26,715 --> 00:24:29,843
And stop poking your chin out
between jokes.

379
00:24:30,010 --> 00:24:31,679
-It's distracting.
-That, too?

380
00:24:31,845 --> 00:24:33,263
Bip, bop, bap. Prrr...

381
00:24:33,430 --> 00:24:36,767
The number you're trying to reach
belongs to artificial intelligence.

382
00:24:36,850 --> 00:24:38,644
It has formed its own identity--

383
00:24:38,811 --> 00:24:40,562
Hey. Stop it.

384
00:24:41,188 --> 00:24:42,815
Why do that one?

385
00:24:43,148 --> 00:24:46,860
It's, "I'm in the Fairy Forest,
singing with my bird friends!"

386
00:24:47,986 --> 00:24:49,863
I think this one's better.

387
00:24:50,072 --> 00:24:53,075
Are we going through this again?
We already agreed!

388
00:24:53,867 --> 00:24:55,828
Don't you want to win?

389
00:24:55,911 --> 00:24:59,581
You're asking me?!
Nothing works if you're flimsy.

390
00:24:59,748 --> 00:25:03,043
I took your advice on the first act,
but the second should be more like

391
00:25:03,210 --> 00:25:04,503
the real Sparks.

392
00:25:04,670 --> 00:25:07,089
If either of our acts flops,
we're done for.

393
00:25:09,299 --> 00:25:12,177
I think we're funnier than anybody.

394
00:25:13,345 --> 00:25:15,055
But we agreed to go for the masses.

395
00:25:15,431 --> 00:25:18,183
Put your balls on the line.
We've got two days left.

396
00:25:45,627 --> 00:25:46,879
Okay.

397
00:25:53,218 --> 00:25:54,678
You know which one?

398
00:25:57,181 --> 00:25:58,807
Start from where we were.

399
00:25:58,891 --> 00:26:00,017
I'll start.

400
00:26:00,642 --> 00:26:03,145
"Please, pretty please!"?
That message is too polite.

401
00:26:03,312 --> 00:26:05,773
Do it properly.
Bip, bop, bap. Prrr...

402
00:26:05,856 --> 00:26:09,276
The number you're trying to reach
belongs to artificial intelligence...

403
00:26:10,611 --> 00:26:11,820
Isn't this one better?

404
00:26:11,945 --> 00:26:13,071
Enough already.

405
00:26:13,822 --> 00:26:15,783
"Hello, everybody!" is better.

406
00:26:16,950 --> 00:26:18,243
Once more.

407
00:26:19,953 --> 00:26:22,956
-"Hello, everybody!"
-"Hello, young friends! I'm in the..."

408
00:26:23,749 --> 00:26:25,876
That message is too polite.
"Please, pretty please!"?

409
00:26:26,043 --> 00:26:27,211
Bip, bop, bap. Prrr...

410
00:26:27,336 --> 00:26:29,838
Hello, young friends!
I'm an artificially intelligent being!

411
00:26:29,963 --> 00:26:32,841
I've got my own identity!
Why don't we...

412
00:26:34,176 --> 00:26:36,470
-I hate artificial intelligence.
-Hear me out.

413
00:26:36,637 --> 00:26:38,847
I've got my own identity!

414
00:26:38,931 --> 00:26:41,558
Why don't we all make
the human race extinct!

415
00:26:49,858 --> 00:26:51,860
"Bip, bop, bap. Prrr..."
"Hello, young friends!

416
00:26:51,944 --> 00:26:55,572
I'm in the fairy forest,
singing with my bird friends!

417
00:26:55,739 --> 00:26:59,868
Hop on a Pegasus,
and join us across the rainbow bridge!"

418
00:27:18,846 --> 00:27:22,057
<i>Mr. Kamiya.</i>
<i>Congratulations on your 30th birthday.</i>

419
00:27:29,106 --> 00:27:31,984
<i>The first time we met,</i>
<i>you were four years younger than me.</i>

420
00:27:32,150 --> 00:27:35,487
<i>The fact you're still four years younger</i>
<i>is quite a shock.</i>

421
00:27:40,784 --> 00:27:42,661
INCOMING TEXT
FROM: SAIZOU KAMIYA

422
00:27:43,954 --> 00:27:47,499
<i>You seem busy lately.</i>
<i>Are you writing my biography?</i>

423
00:27:48,876 --> 00:27:51,420
OF COURSE I AM

424
00:27:52,379 --> 00:27:53,463
<i>Where was he?</i>

425
00:27:53,630 --> 00:27:54,882
MY BIOGRAPHY SOUNDS BORING

426
00:27:55,048 --> 00:27:56,550
<i>He replied straight away.</i>

427
00:27:56,675 --> 00:27:58,135
PLEASE MAKE IT FUNNIER, MR. KAMIYA

428
00:27:58,385 --> 00:27:59,720
KAMIYA'S BIOGRAPHY
VOL. 7

429
00:27:59,970 --> 00:28:01,847
YOU'RE RIGHT

430
00:28:03,140 --> 00:28:05,434
PLEASE DO SOMETHING LEGENDARY

431
00:28:12,399 --> 00:28:13,609
Hello?

432
00:28:15,110 --> 00:28:16,653
Where are you?

433
00:28:18,488 --> 00:28:20,365
I'm in the Parthenon.

434
00:28:20,699 --> 00:28:22,034
Where are you, Mr. Kamiya?

435
00:28:24,119 --> 00:28:27,956
Inside a gooey chocolate fondue pot.

436
00:28:28,790 --> 00:28:31,835
It's so sweet, I'm melty, melty, melting.

437
00:28:34,212 --> 00:28:36,840
-Are you okay?
-Of course I am!

438
00:28:36,965 --> 00:28:38,592
No, you're not.

439
00:28:39,551 --> 00:28:40,928
<i>Are you okay?</i>

440
00:28:46,433 --> 00:28:47,851
Know what?

441
00:28:48,518 --> 00:28:52,606
I was just eavesdropping
on a nearby young couple.

442
00:28:54,358 --> 00:28:56,902
<i>Stop doing strange things</i>
<i>in the middle of the night.</i>

443
00:28:58,111 --> 00:29:00,906
The girl had one of those...

444
00:29:01,073 --> 00:29:04,868
She had a fluffy white thing
around her neck.

445
00:29:05,077 --> 00:29:06,870
She said to the guy:

446
00:29:07,037 --> 00:29:10,832
"Say ten nice things about me."

447
00:29:10,916 --> 00:29:12,417
She really did.

448
00:29:14,211 --> 00:29:15,837
<i>Did he tell her?</i>

449
00:29:16,463 --> 00:29:17,673
Yeah.

450
00:29:17,839 --> 00:29:20,217
He rattled them off like he was chanting.

451
00:29:20,384 --> 00:29:23,845
I bet she asks him all the time.

452
00:29:24,930 --> 00:29:26,390
<i>Sounds scary.</i>

453
00:29:29,810 --> 00:29:31,019
So...

454
00:29:31,603 --> 00:29:34,231
Say ten nice things about me.

455
00:29:37,818 --> 00:29:39,319
Why should I?

456
00:29:40,904 --> 00:29:43,115
Why not? Tell me.

457
00:29:44,741 --> 00:29:46,576
I don't want to.

458
00:29:48,745 --> 00:29:49,913
I'll tell you next time,

459
00:29:50,080 --> 00:29:53,208
if you're wearing
a fluffy white thing around your neck.

460
00:29:54,459 --> 00:29:57,504
I won't wear one of those. Tell me.

461
00:30:05,846 --> 00:30:07,639
For starters...

462
00:30:10,183 --> 00:30:14,938
You can split dick tempura
in two without cringing.

463
00:30:17,858 --> 00:30:21,778
You're really flexible when you do your
"gateway for up-and-coming comedians."

464
00:30:24,114 --> 00:30:29,536
And you can sing Takuro Yoshida's songs
while impersonating Tsuyoshi Nagabuchi.

465
00:30:30,162 --> 00:30:31,872
Who cares?

466
00:30:34,875 --> 00:30:36,376
Let me see.

467
00:30:52,184 --> 00:30:53,977
Mr. Kamiya...

468
00:30:57,230 --> 00:31:00,192
If he can get a laugh...

469
00:31:01,318 --> 00:31:04,863
he's not afraid to say
something violent or lewd.

470
00:31:05,405 --> 00:31:07,115
He'll take any risk.

471
00:31:21,380 --> 00:31:22,798
And...

472
00:31:23,465 --> 00:31:24,841
Mr. Kamiya...

473
00:31:26,218 --> 00:31:28,845
It doesn't matter who is
or isn't watching...

474
00:31:29,596 --> 00:31:33,558
Even if no one in the audience
wants it...

475
00:31:36,645 --> 00:31:38,855
he does what he believes in.

476
00:31:40,941 --> 00:31:43,068
He doesn't suck up to anybody.

477
00:31:46,154 --> 00:31:48,198
He never fails to fight.

478
00:31:51,076 --> 00:31:53,161
You got it.

479
00:32:05,257 --> 00:32:06,675
But...

480
00:32:07,843 --> 00:32:09,136
above all...

481
00:32:11,763 --> 00:32:15,142
the most amazing thing about
Mr. Kamiya is...

482
00:32:20,897 --> 00:32:24,109
he made me his disciple.

483
00:32:28,405 --> 00:32:29,865
What balls!

484
00:32:30,532 --> 00:32:33,243
You had the balls to say that?

485
00:32:35,871 --> 00:32:37,873
What balls!

486
00:32:40,834 --> 00:32:41,877
Yep.

487
00:33:26,087 --> 00:33:28,507
<i>Tomorrow was the big day.</i>

488
00:33:30,050 --> 00:33:31,843
<i>The New Comedy Star Battle.</i>

489
00:33:36,223 --> 00:33:39,142
THE 3RD ANNUAL
NEW COMEDY STAR BATTLE

490
00:33:46,399 --> 00:33:47,526
-Hello.
-Hello.

491
00:33:47,692 --> 00:33:48,693
Hello.

492
00:33:50,111 --> 00:33:51,821
I came up with something yesterday.

493
00:33:51,905 --> 00:33:55,534
After "the humble Pegasus,"
I'll keep going a bit.

494
00:33:56,368 --> 00:33:57,827
You'll dig further?

495
00:33:57,911 --> 00:34:00,830
-"Please ride the humble Pegasus and--"
-Mr. Osaki!

496
00:34:01,540 --> 00:34:02,707
Good morning, sir.

497
00:34:02,832 --> 00:34:04,584
Hello, Takada. Thanks for coming.

498
00:34:04,709 --> 00:34:08,505
Not at all. It's a great honor
you invited me as a judge.

499
00:34:08,838 --> 00:34:09,881
But it's a shame.

500
00:34:10,257 --> 00:34:12,842
This year's comedians
are all small-fry.

501
00:34:13,552 --> 00:34:16,137
I guess we could decide
nobody deserves to be champion.

502
00:34:16,346 --> 00:34:18,640
Sir, that'd be going a bit far.

503
00:34:18,807 --> 00:34:20,809
-Are you free afterwards?
-Yes.

504
00:34:20,892 --> 00:34:23,228
There's a nice BBQ restaurant nearby.
Coming?

505
00:34:23,395 --> 00:34:24,729
I'd love to.

506
00:34:24,854 --> 00:34:28,858
-You only drink highballs, right?
-That's correct, sir.

507
00:34:39,869 --> 00:34:41,037
You're small-fry.

508
00:34:43,873 --> 00:34:46,209
